<font color="#FF0000">MY CAPTAIN, MY CAPTAIN</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jul 18 18:18:29 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Talk about an agenda, I understood my captain in Nam quite well.<br><br>
I remember the Stars and Stripes story on our captain, I believe he was standing on a tank. 45 cal. drawn out, leading his troops into Dodge City. Great picture and an excellent photo opportunity. <br><br>
The story said, something to the effect...<br>
Captain Charles S. Robb under heavy enemy fire. <br><br>
Truth was no such thing happened. The tanks were stuck in the mud, earlier that day I had been walking point. We were ambushed by about 30 NVA who were no more then 15 meters away. <br>
 The rest of the company were out of harms way, around a bend in the river and a small knoll. <br>
I and the guy behind me hit the deck returned fire and waited for help.  By the time the rest of the company came around the river's bend to help us (about 30 minutes later, command decisions needed to be made, you know), the gooks were long gone. <br><br>
However, A Marine later did step on a bobby-trap but they did not even medivacked him out. The heavy combat thing, however made the papers back home.<br><br>
Just before I left, we had become idle. Sitting on a hill filling sand bags, can't take too many risks you know. <br>
However, I do recall wonder-boy Pat Nugent (the President's other son-in-law, AKA fly-boy, dropped that orange stuff all over Nam) one day visiting us on hill 65. later that day he wanted to play with the 50-caliber in the tower and got upset when a Marine slapped his hands away. <br>
He went and got Robbie and we had to let him play with the gun. <br>

